    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided unaudited segment operating and financial data from the S-1 prospectus and MD&A, here are the extracted details regarding Starlink\'s subscriber counts, pricing, ARPU, and Connectivity segment operating metrics:\n\n### 1. Starlink Subscriber Counts\nStarlink has experienced rapid year-over-year growth in its consumer and business subscription base. \n* **Q1 2026 (Three Months Ended March 31, 2026):** 10.3 million subscribers (up ~105% or 104.7% YoY).\n* **Q1 2025 (Three Months Ended March 31, 2025):** 5.0 million subscribers.\n* **FY 2025 (Year Ended December 31, 2025):** 8.9 million subscribers.\n* **FY 2024:** 4.4 million subscribers.\n* **FY 2023:** 2.3 million subscribers.\n* **Market Reach:** As of March 31, 2026, subscribers are spread across 164 countries, territories, and markets, representing a fraction of the estimated 3.3 billion potential end users in those regions.\n* **Definition:** A "Starlink Subscriber" is defined as a unique *Service Line* directly assigned to a Starlink.com account. It includes Personal (Residential, Roam) and Business (Local/Global Priority) plans but **excludes** managed enterprise and government customers with directly negotiated contracts. Multiple end-users or devices can share a single Service Line.\n\n### 2. Pricing Strategy & Models\n* **Consumer Pricing:** Subscribers are charged a monthly subscription fee that varies based on geographic market and download speed, plus a typically one-time upfront terminal (kit) cost. The company has been actively adding "lower-priced service plans" to make the service affordable and accessible across different global economic contexts.\n* **Enterprise Pricing:** Enterprise contracts utilize a combination of subscriptions, data consumption, capacity, or other customized pricing models.\n* **Global TAM ARPU Assumptions (Market Sizing):**\n  * **Residential Broadband:** Assumes a global weighted average monthly ARPU of **$31** ($43 in high-income, $16 in upper-middle, and $9 in lower-middle/low-income markets).\n  * **Starlink Mobile:** Assumes a global weighted average monthly mobile ARPU of **$8** per user ($18 in high-income, $5 in upper-middle, and $2 in lower-middle/low-income markets).\n\n### 3. Starlink ARPU (Average Revenue Per User)\nARPU is calculated as service revenue generated from Starlink Subscribers divided by the average number of subscribers and the number of months in the period. The company\'s strategy prioritizes scale and global market access over maximizing ARPU, leading to a deliberate, ongoing decline in the metric.\n* **Q1 2026:** $66 / month (down 22.9% YoY)\n* **Q1 2025:** $86 / month\n* **FY 2025:** $81 / month (down 11.2% YoY)\n* **FY 2024:** $91 / month (down 8.1% YoY)\n* **FY 2023:** $99 / month\n* **Future Outlook:** ARPU is expected to continue declining over the next few years due to international expansion (growing the subscriber base outside North America), the introduction of lower-priced service plans, and adjustments to monthly broadband fees. This will be offset by increased scale and technological advancements reducing operational costs.\n\n### 4. Connectivity Segment Operating & Financial Metrics\nThe Connectivity segment encompasses Starlink\'s consumer, enterprise, and government broadband and mobile services.\n\n**Financial Performance (in millions):**\n| Metric | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Income from Operations** | $1,188 | $1,033 | $4,423 | $2,006 | $469 |\n| **Adjusted EBITDA** | $2,087 | $1,618 | $7,168 | $3,849 | $1,602 |\n\n**Revenue & Cost Drivers:**\n* **Revenue Growth:** Q1 2026 Connectivity revenue grew by $782M (31.6% YoY). This was driven by a $656M increase in consumer revenue (massive subscriber growth offsetting ARPU declines) and a $126M increase in enterprise/government revenue (driven by aviation, maritime, and mobility, though partially offset by a decrease in government connectivity).\n* **Cost of Revenue:** Q1 2026 costs increased by $437M (36.0% YoY). Primary drivers include higher depreciation ($276M) from capitalized launch and satellite costs due to increased Starlink flights, and higher ground operating, customer support, payment processing, freight, and warranty costs.\n* **R&D Expenses:** Increased by $82M in Q1 2026, driven by next-generation satellite production development and Starlink Kits.\n\n**Network Scale & Performance Metrics (as of March 31, 2026):**\n* **Satellite Constellation:** ~9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in Low-Earth Orbit (LEO), accounting for ~75% of all active maneuverable satellites in orbit.\n* **Performance:** Median latency of ~25 milliseconds; median download speeds of 225 Mbps during peak hours for residential users.\n* **Future Capacity:** Preparing to deploy next-generation V3 satellites (1 Tbps downlink capacity per satellite) via Starship in H2 2026, which will allow up to 60 V3 satellites per launch (a 20-fold capacity increase over Falcon 9).',
