    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the S-1 Registration Statement and Financial Statements, here is the detailed extraction of information regarding intercompany transactions, transfer pricing policies, related party transactions, and Elon Musk’s compensation.\n\n### 1. Intercompany Transactions\nThe text highlights the accounting treatment of intercompany transactions following the mergers of SpaceX, xAI, and X (formerly Twitter) under common control:\n*   **Elimination in Consolidation:** The mergers were accounted for as reorganizations of entities under common control because Elon Musk held a controlling financial interest in all entities. Consequently, the consolidated financial statements reflect a retrospective combination, and **all historical related party/intercompany transactions between SpaceX, xAI, and X have been eliminated in consolidation.**\n*   **No Step-Up in Basis:** No new goodwill or other intangible assets were recorded during these intercompany mergers; net assets were combined at their historical carrying amounts.\n\n### 2. Transfer Pricing (Arm\'s Length Policies)\nWhile the specific term "transfer pricing" is not explicitly used, the document outlines the company\'s **arm\'s length pricing policy** for cross-company and related-party transactions:\n*   **Standardized Commercial Terms:** Transactions with Tesla (and other affiliated entities) are conducted on terms **"no less favorable to SpaceX than those generally available to unaffiliated third parties under similar circumstances."** \n*   **Aircraft Usage Rates:** Aircraft usage invoiced to Tesla is charged at rates mutually determined by Tesla and SpaceX, strictly subject to Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) rules governing such arrangements.\n*   **Vehicle Purchases:** Cybertrucks were purchased from Tesla at the **manufacturer’s suggested retail price (MSRP)**, ensuring a standardized, market-based transfer price.\n\n### 3. Related Party Transactions\nThe company engages in extensive related party transactions with entities owned by or affiliated with Elon Musk, as well as with board members. \n\n**Transactions with Tesla:**\n*   **Goods & Services (SpaceX):** Purchased $11M (2023), $4M (2024), $144M (2025), and $0.2M (Jan-Feb 2026).\n*   **Goods & Services (xAI):** Purchased $191M (2024), $506M (2025), and $34M (Jan-Feb 2026). xAI also recognized revenue from Tesla of $2M (2025) and $0.4M (Jan-Feb 2026).\n*   **Capital Expenditures:** Purchased $191M (2024) and $506M (2025) in Megapack products. Purchased $131M in Cybertrucks at MSRP (2025).\n*   **Advertising (X Platform):** Tesla purchased advertising on X totaling $0.5M (2024) and $4M (2025).\n*   **Aircraft Leasing:** SpaceX charged Tesla $1M (2023), $1M (2024), and $2M (2025) for the use of SpaceX-owned aircraft.\n*   **Equity Investment:** In Jan 2026, Tesla agreed to invest $2,000M in xAI Series E Preferred Stock. Post-merger, this converted into the right to acquire SpaceX Class A common stock, resulting in the issuance of 3.8 million shares to Tesla in March 2026. (Tesla also holds ~18.99M shares of SpaceX Class A stock, representing <1.0% ownership).\n\n**Transactions with Other Musk-Affiliated Entities:**\n*   **The Boring Company:** X paid lease payments of $0.1M (2024), $1M (2025), and $0.1M (Jan-Feb 2026). SpaceX incurred $1M (2025) for tunnel construction in Bastrop, Texas.\n*   **Musk Industries LLC:** xAI paid lease payments of $0.5M (2024), $2M (2025), and $0.2M (Jan-Feb 2026).\n*   **Security Services:** SpaceX paid a Musk-owned security company $2M (2023), $3M (2024), $4M (2025), and $1M (Jan-Feb 2026) for Musk\'s personal and SpaceX-related security.\n*   **Craft Aviation Services:** Paid $1M (2023), $1M (2024), $3M (2025), and $1M (Jan-Feb 2026) for aircraft maintenance.\n*   **Personal Aircraft Reimbursement:** SpaceX reimbursed Musk for using his personal aircraft for business travel: $0.1M (2023), $3M (2024), $2M (2025), and $0.2M (Jan-Feb 2026).\n\n**Transactions with Valor Equity Partners (Antonio J. Gracias, Board Member):**\n*   **Failed Sale-Leasebacks:** xAI subsidiary CTC entered into AI hardware lease agreements with Valor. These were deemed "failed sale-leaseback transactions," resulting in the recording of $455M (current) and $4,052M (non-current) in debt, plus $66M in interest expense (2025). A second transaction (Valor transaction II) resulted in an additional $5,365M in recorded debt.\n\n**Secondary Stock Purchases:**\n*   In 2025, Elon Musk purchased **$1,421 million** of common stock from current and former employees through his trust.\n\n### 4. Elon Musk Compensation\nHistorically, the board made all decisions regarding Musk\'s compensation. Musk and Gwynne Shotwell do not receive additional cash or equity compensation for their services as directors. However, Musk is the recipient of massive, performance-based equity awards and perquisites:\n\n**Performance-Based Equity Awards:**\n*   **AI CEO Award (xAI/SpaceX):** Originally granted as the "xAI Award" in Nov 2025, it was cancelled and replaced in March 2026 with the "AI CEO Award" consisting of **302.1 million performance-based restricted shares** of Class B common stock. \n    *   *Vesting Conditions:* (i) Market cap milestones across 12 tranches ranging from $1.065 trillion to $6.565 trillion (in $500B increments); and (ii) Completion of non-Earth-based data centers capable of delivering 100 terawatts of compute per year. \n    *   *Accounting:* Grant date fair value was $91.47 to $95.92 per share. Treated as an accounting modification; no incremental expense is recognized until new performance conditions are deemed probable.\n*   **SpaceX CEO Award (Mars Colony Award):** Granted in January 2026, consisting of **1,000 million (1 billion) performance-based restricted shares** of Class B common stock.\n    *   *Vesting Conditions:* (i) Market cap milestones across 15 tranches ranging from $500 billion to $7.5 trillion; and (ii) The establish