istorical on-orbit performance, propellant life, orbit-raise timing, and planned transitions to newer technology.\n\n### 4. Depreciation Schedules & Policies\n*   **General PP&E:** Depreciated using the straight-line method over estimated useful lives.\n*   **Flight Vehicles & Spacecraft (Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Dragon):** Depreciated based on the **expected number of average flights** rather than a time-based schedule.\n    *   **Falcon 9 / Heavy Boosters:** Engineered and demonstrated to support up to 40 flights. However, the **maximum accounting useful life is capped at 25 flights**. This conservative estimate accounts for the strategic transition to Starship (which will reduce Falcon demand) and government contract restrictions (some prohibit using boosters flown more than 5 times).\n    *   **Second Stages:** Non-reusable; recorded as inventory and expensed to cost of revenue upon launch.\n    *   **Dragon Capsule:** Fully reusable; classified as PP&E and depreciated to cost of revenue.\n*   **Leasehold Improvements:** Depreciated over the shorter of their estimated useful lives or the related lease term.\n*   **Starship (Future):** Post-commercialization, it will be capitalized and depreciated in the cost of revenue of the segment associated with the delivered payload.\n\n### 5. Unit Economics & Reusability Impact\n*   **Hardware Reusability:** The core unit economic advantage is the recovery, refurbishment, and reflying of key hardware (boosters, fairings, Merlin engines). This minimizes hardware replacement expenses and spreads fixed costs over multiple flights.\n*   **Pricing Strategy:** Missions launching on flight-proven (reused) boosters are generally priced below traditional expendable flights.\n*   **Refurbishment Economics:** The expected flight life of hardware is continuously evaluated based on recovery success rates, the economic feasibility of declining refurbishment costs, and customer acceptance limits.\n*   **Cost Capitalization:** Increased re