he Space segment\'s income statement, SpaceX relies on operational metrics to track the true scale and throughput of its launch capabilities:\n* **Mass to Orbit & Launch Count:** SpaceX uses "Mass to Orbit" and total "Launches" as key business metrics for the Space segment. The document notes that these operational metrics *"grow more rapidly than Space segment revenue because these metrics include our internal constellation deployments from which we do not recognize inter-segment revenue."*\n* **Strategic Value vs. Financial Reflection:** The S-1 notes that while the Space segment\'s revenue scale may appear lower relative to its massive launch cadence, its financial results *"do not reflect the foundational strategic value that it provides to us in bolstering the growth of our Connectivity and AI segments."*\n\n**Summary:** \nSpaceX does not charge Starlink a "price" for launches. The Space segment acts as the backbone for the Connectivity segment by absorbing the operational execution, while the raw costs of those internal launches are pushed directly onto the Connectivity segment\'s balance sheet as capitalized satellite assets, eventually flowing through the Connectivity segment\'s income statement as depreciation expense.',
